<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      3 men have 4 coats, 6 paints, and 5 caps. In how many ways can they wear them?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
<p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
      coats &amp; paints &amp; caps \\ \hline 
      ^4P_3 &amp; ^6P_3 &amp; ^5P_3  \\ 
      \end{array}
  </me>
</p>

    <p>
     <me> = ^4P_3\times ^6P_3 \times ^5P_3 </me> 
     each of these outfits are compulsory to complete dressed up for the men, 
     hence multiplication principle is used here to find the total ways of wearing them.
     <me>
      =\frac{4!}{1!} \times \frac{6!}{3!}\times \frac{5!}{2!} = \frac{4!\times 6\times 5\times \times 4!\times 5\times 4!}{3!\times 2!} = 172800.
     </me>
       </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      How many different signals can be made by using any number of flags from <m>4</m> flags of different colors?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>

<p>
  <me>
    \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
    \text{ I signal} &amp; \text{ II signal} &amp; \text{ III signal}  &amp; \text{ IV signal} \\ \hline 
    ^4P_1 &amp; ^4P_2 &amp; ^4P_3  &amp; ^4P_4 \\ 
    \end{array}
</me>
</p>


 <p>
  <me> = ^4P_1\times ^4P_2 \times ^4P_3 \times ^4P_4</me> 
  Every signals are complete and independent on each other, 
  hence addition principle is used to find the total numbers of signals.
  <me>
   =\frac{4!}{3!} + \frac{4!}{2!}\times \frac{4!}{1!} \times \frac{4!}{0!} = 4+12+24+24 = 64.
  </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A code is to consist of two distinct letters followed by two distinct numbers between 1 and 9. 
      For example, CA35, DQ72, etc. are codes.
      <ol marker ="i">
        <li>
          <p>
            How many such codes are there?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            How many of them end with an even integer?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>

    <p>
      <me>
        \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
        \text{ I  alphabet} &amp; \text{ II  alphabet} &amp; \text{ I digit}  &amp; \text{ II digit} \\ \hline 
        26 &amp; 25 &amp; 9  &amp; 8 \\ 
        \end{array}
    </me>
    </p>

   
    <p>
      <ol marker ="i">
        <li>
          <p>
            We need distinct alphabets and digits to make codes. Hence the total codes are <m>26\times 25\times 9\times 8 = 46800. </m>. 
          </p>
          <p>
            or, we have -  <me> = ^{26}P_2\times ^9P_2 =  \frac{26!}{24!} \times \frac{9!}{7!} = 26\times 25\times 9\times 8 = 46800.</me> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For even number on units place there are 4 choices <m>2, 4, 6, 8</m> and we need distinct 
            numbers on each place so remaining 8-digits are only available for tens place. Hence, 
            <me> = ^{26}P_2\times 8 \times 4 = 26\times 25\times 8\times 4 = 20800. </me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        <me>
          \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
          \text{ I  alphabet} &amp; \text{ II  alphabet} &amp; \text{ I digit}  &amp; \text{ even no.} \\ \hline 
          26 &amp; 25 &amp; 8  &amp; 4 \\ 
          \end{array}
      </me>
      </p>

  </solution>

</example>

