<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      There are 2 english, 3 spanish, and 4 hebrew books. In how many ways can 
      they be arranged on a self so as to keep all the books of the same language toghether?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>

    <p>
      <me>
        \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
        \text{ E1, E2 } &amp; \text{ S1, S2, S3 } &amp; \text{ H1, H2, H3, H4 }  \\ \hline 
        \text{ 1 object} &amp; \text{ 1 object} &amp; \text{ 1 object}   \\ 
        \end{array}
    </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider each language book as one bundle, so there are three bundles (objects). 
       Hence, the number of ways we can arrange these bundles is given as 
      <me>
        ^3P_3
      </me>
      Now, among each books in a bundle can be suffled together, hence, internal arrangements are given as 
      <me>
        ^2P_2 \times ^3P_3 \times ^4P_4
      </me>
      Here, each tasks are compulsory to complete the work. Hence, the total number of ways to arrange the whole books are 
      <me>
        ^3P_3 \times ^2P_2 \times ^3P_3 \times ^4P_4 = 3! \times 2! \times 3! \times 4! = ......
      </me>
      
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      In how many ways can 7 test papers be arranged so that the best and the worst papers are never come together?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
     P1, P2, P3, P4, P5, P6, P7
    </p>
    <p>
      Here, the total arrangements are <m>^7P_7</m> for all papers together.
    </p>

    <p>
      <me>
        \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
        \text{ P1, P2, P3, P4, P5 } &amp; \text{ P6, P7 }   \\ \hline 
        \text{ 5 object} &amp; \text{ 1 object}   \\ 
        \end{array}
    </me>
    </p>


   <p>
    Now, number of ways in which the best and the worst papers come together is given by 
    <m>^6P_6 \times ^2P_2</m>. First bundle of papers <m>P1, P2, P3, P4, P5</m> considered as 5 objects. 
    and the second bundle <m>P6, P7 </m> is considered as 1 object, as they are coming together.
   </p>
   <p>
    Hence, the number of ways when best and worst papers never come together is given by 
    <me>
      ^7P_7 - \left( ^6P_6 \times ^2P_2 \right) = 7! -(6!\times 2!) = ....
    </me>
    
   </p>
  </solution>
</example>


