<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      In how many ways can 3 prizes be distributed among 4 boys, when 
      <ol marker ="i">
        <li>
          <p>
            No boys get more than 1 prize,
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            A boy may get any number of prizes,
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            No boy gets all the prizes?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Here, we have prizes: <m>P1, P2, P3</m> and boys: <m>B1, B2, B3, B4</m> 
      <ol marker ="i">
        <li>
          <p>
            First prize can be received by any one of the boys, so 4 choice, and 3 choice, and so on.
            <m>4\times 3 \times 2 \times 1 = 4!.</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>4\times 4 \times 4 \times 4 = 4^3 = 64.</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Boy gets all the prizes - all prizes go to any one of the boys.
            <m>64-4 =60.</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

